It is with great dismay that I want to announce that I have postponed the 2020-2021 school year, homecoming festivities until the week of January 25th. We will plan to hold all of the activities as normal as we can during basketball season.

-Homecoming week will start on January 25th.
-Homecoming basketball game will be on Saturday, January 30th @ 3:00pm, as the girls/boys basketball team will take on Chariton.
-Homecoming dance will follow @ 7:00pm in the Elementary Safe Room.
All other details will be communicated out as we get closer

I have created a short video that explains this as well.

https://www.loom.com/share/06ceca484cc2443988ff3a1c4781c4e8

Thank you for your continued support and understanding during this unprecedented time in our lives.

Landon Miller
High School Principal

post_text:
Last night was the Cardinal Cross Country teams first meet of the season! Our top 3 runners from the high school boys team were Gavin Grove, who finished 18th with a time of 19:00.9, Gunner Zugg, who finished 37th with a time of 20:11.4, and Karson Kirkpatrick, who finished 67th with a time of 22:31.8.

Our top 3 runners from the high school girls team were Alexia McClure, who finished 26th with a time of 24:41.0, Allison Sloan, who finished 27th with a time of 24:45.7 and Caitlyn Reber, who finished 31st with a time of 25:02.2.

Our next meet will be on Tuesday, September 8th at Riverview Country Club in Keosauqua. Junior high will run at 4:30 followed by high school girls at 5:10 and high school boys at 5:45.

Our top 3 runners from the high school girls team were Alexia McClure, who finished 26th with a time of 24:41.0, Allison Sloan, who finished 27th with a time of 24:45.7 and Caitlyn Reber, who finished 31st with a time of 25:02.2.

post_text:
Parents and Guardians,
Thank you so much for your patience with our elementary drop off and pick up. If you are traveling southbound on Hwy 16 from the four lane, we encourage you to use the new gravel driveway. If you park in our new gravel lot and walk up to pick up or drop off, this process will be the quickest option. This change is an effort to increase the safety and to speed up the pick up and drop off process. Our car rider and drop lanes are still available and we will help escort your child to the vehicle. We ask that you do not park in our circle drive and stay in your vehicle during pick up and drop off. If your child needs help buckling in, you are encouraged to hop out to buckle them up. Thank you for your partnership with student safety before and after school.

If you need to pick up your student early for any reason this school year, please call the office and we will get your student out to your car.

Parents of 7th Grade Students - Proof of Tdap booster and Meningococcal vaccination before the first day of school.

Reminder that graduation is 1 week away!

*Graduation practice is Saturday (8/8) at 10:00am. Graduates please enter through the student parking lot doors on the west side. You will be screened as you enter. Please do not come if you are having symptoms or not feeling well. BRING YOUR GRADUATION ATTIRE SO WE CAN MAKE SURE YOU HAVE EVERYTHING YOU NEED.

*The 2020 Graduation Ceremony is Sunday (8/9) at 2:00pm. Graduates will enter the South side High School, Main Entrance where there will be staff waiting to screen you and give you further instructions. Please remember that you are allowed 4 guests per graduate. Other guests may receive graduates, after the ceremony, on the EAST lawn outside the school. Please social distance at that time.

During all of these activities we encourage masks by attendees, but they are not required.

We will TRY to LIVE STREAM and/or record the ceremony. We are working on setting up the technology at this time.

If you have questions, please email Landon.Miller@cardinalcomet.com.

post_text:
Will families have the option to keep their students home for this school year?

Yes, a virtual option will be available for families who have concerns about sending their child back to school. Cardinal Virtual Learning Academy will look different from last spring and if you choose this option, attendance and grades will be taken each day. The required online learning will include recorded instruction, classroom discussions, opportunities for online assessments, and more. An online platform at each building will house the lessons and student assignments. Families who have indicated a preference for the online learning model will be contacted with more details regarding the expectations. If you choose the online option for this school year, please register your child below using this link:

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfVlWUfwYAyt5jOZXV4LBTULrb2q_GgD3psER7blRdsul7HJw/viewform?usp=sf_link

Will families have the option to keep their students home for this school year?

Yes, a virtual option will be available for families who have concerns about sending their child back to school. This option will look different from last spring and if you choose this option, attendance and grades will be taken each day. The required online
learning will include recorded instruction, classroom discussions,
opportunities for online assessments, and more. An online platform at each building will house the lessons and student assignments. Families who have indicated a preference for the online learning model will be contacted with more details regarding the expectations. If you choose the online option for
this school year, please register your child below using this link:

Virtual Online Learning Sign Up:

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfVlWUfwYAyt5jOZXV4LBTULrb2q_GgD3psER7blRdsul7HJw/viewform?usp=sf_link

Cardinal Parents and Guardians:

We know that many of our families have completed the Iowa technology survey with our school secretaries over the past week. Thank you for helping us. This survey is very important as it allows Cardinal CSD to qualify for funding to help with internet connectivity and computers for our families. The governor allocated 26 million dollars for this need but schools must submit data to be able to receive funding.

Please take this 5 minute survey if you have not already completed it with a district secretary. Thank you for consideration

Survey link: http://bit.ly/iowatechsurvey

shared_text:
Lil' Comets Youth Football
June 18 at 9:38 AM ·

Hey Comets! My name is John Torres and I am a new coach here at Cardinal. I will be coaching high school football as well as overseeing the youth program. At this time we are planning to have a season for youth football. We are going to be in the Ottumwa Youth Football League. We are still working out the details but as I know more I will relay the message back to everybody. This will be for students in 5th and 6th grades. If anybody knows any 5th or 6th grader that is interested in playing football, encourage them to like the facebook page and we will keep putting information on this page. If you are younger than 5th grade and are wondering about flag football, more information will come out as we get closer to August. If anybody has any questions my email is John.Torres@cardinalcomet.com don’t hesitate to email me with any questions. Go Comets!!

Some changes are being made to food distribution for the summer. This Tuesday pickup will be from 5:00 -6:00 at the high school and 5:00-5:30 at Eldon, Agency, and Batavia parks. You will receive meals for Wednesday and Thursday.

From June 4th to August 20th pickups and deliveries will only be held on Thursdays. Every Thursday you will receive a one week supply for breakfast and lunch. Every Thursday you will be able to pick up from Eldon, Agency, and Batavia parks from
5:00 - 530 and at the high school from 5:00-7:00.

If you have any questions or no longer require deliveries of meal supplies please contact Heather Smith at: heather.smith@cardinalcomet.com.

We wish you and your family a safe and healthy summer.

post_text: Any MS boy interested in playing Babe Ruth, they opened up sign ups. It’s a great way to get some baseball in since the MS season was cancelled.
shared_text:
Ottumwa Babe Ruth
May 21 at 10:27 PM ·

Ottumwa Babe Ruth will be playing a season this year. We will be posting more info as we know more information. As of now we will be having tryouts for all players so we can draft teams. Tryouts for 13 year old will be June 1 from 6-10pm. Tryouts for 14,15 and 16 year olds will be June 2 from 6-9pm with the draft to follow. We are taking late signups but must be signed up before the draft starts. We are going to spread the tryouts out in smaller groups during the days assigned. You will be notified May 29 as to what time you are asked to be there for tryouts. Practice will begin after players are assigned to teams and games will be played until season date end of July 31. We are looking into all the precautions as to make this as safe as we can for everyone.

post_text:
🎉Farewell Reverse Parade🎉

We are so excited to be holding an Elementary and Middle School "Reverse Parade" to see our students and families one last time before summer! Please come see us Thursday May 21st from 5:30-6:30.

Our faculty and staff will line the side of the elementary building and the back fence line to wave and wish you farewell before summer.

Important details are as follows:
--Please enter from HWY 16. This will be one way traffic traveling on the side of the elementary school building. You will be exiting past the athletic center behind the Middle School/High School.
--Please see our map below.
--Please remain in your vehicles and keep moving.
--If possible, please put a piece of paper on your car with your child/childrens' names so we can more easily identify them from afar.
--Feel free to open those windows, sunroofs and turn on some tunes

We have missed you, and we can't wait to see you Thursday from 5:30-6:30!

Tim Albert
Mike Kayser

This spring, we lost a school board member who has served our district for 13 years. Carol Streeby devoted her life to serving her community and the students of our district in many ways. Thank you to all of our past and current school board members!

Cardinal Community School District
April 19 at 4:52 PM ·

Guess what 2020 Seniors? We are not ready to say goodbye just yet! On May 15th from 8 am to 10 am the Cardinal Lunch Staff will prepare your traditional Senior Breakfast! You have earned it and you deserve it! The Cardinal Staff will line the drive to wave goodbye. You will enter through the elementary drive and proceed to the high school kitchen entrance where you will receive a hot breakfast in a to go container. You will also have a special Senior sign with your name on it, you may pull up to the high school entrance and someone will retrieve your sign for you as a keepsake. Congratulations, you will be missed!

*Paid for by the Junior Class

Breakfast will be:
Eggs
Bacon (the real stuff)
hash browns
fresh mixed fruit
muffin
milk
OJ

Please fill out the below survey to RSVP! Make sure to wear your caps and gowns!

Iowa 4-H: Wapello County
May 5 at 12:54 PM ·

The Wapello County 4-H Foundation is honored to announce that they have awarded seven - $500 scholarships to youth who are currently active Wapello County 4-H members.
This scholarship recognizes an outstanding 4-H member who demonstrates leadership and citizenship skills, and is respectful of others and their opinions. They demonstrate service and contributions to their club, their community, our country, and our world. This young person must exhibit evidence of influence of 4-H training in their life, such as career choices, life skills, and interests that adhere to the ideals of the 4-H Program.
The Wapello County 4-H Foundation is proud to recognize the following individuals as the 2020 4-H Foundation Scholarship recipients:
Alan Angle, Eddyville-Blakesburg-Fremont High School
Madison Baskett, Davis County HERALD Program
Kacey Beinhart, Eddyville-Blakesburg-Fremont High School
Tyler Clubb, Ottumwa High School

Kaitlyn Emery, Pekin High School

This is Robin Leonard.

post_text:
This is Mrs. Shelley Peters.
She is a Reading Recovery/Title 1 Reading teacher in the elementary building, and instructional coach.

She leads our Reading Corps program-which reached many students who need an extra boost of reading instruction.
She is our PTO (Parent Teacher Organization)-which advocates for our students and little extras for our teachers! Some works of the PTO include (but are not limited to): hosting Scholastic book fairs, providing funding for teachers, and supporting Cardinal’s projects.
*Reach out if you’re a parent wanting to join/help out!

We appreciate Mrs. Peters' commitment to Cardinal Community School District. She is family to us!
In times of trial and tribulation she still wore a smile and lent a helping hand.

We are lucky to have such a literacy expert on our team.
